2026-06-09 19:23:43,241 DEBUG Tool call: submit_final_result({'final_result': '## Implied Revenue-Per-Launch: SpaceX vs. Rocket Lab — Directional Comparison\n\n---\n\n### 1. Rocket Lab\'s Explicitly Disclosed Per-Launch Economics (Electron)\n\nRocket Lab\'s FY2025 10-K (filed February 26, 2026) provides an unusually granular set of per-launch operating KPIs for its Electron vehicle:\n\n| Metric | FY2023 | FY2024 | FY2025 |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Launch Services Revenue | $71.9M | $125.4M | $199.0M |\n| Electron Launches Completed | 10 | 16 | 21 |\n| **Revenue per Launch (disclosed KPI)** | **$7.1M** | **$7.8M** | **$8.5M** |\n| Cost per Launch (disclosed KPI) | $7.0M | $5.7M | $4.8M |\n| Implied Gross Margin per Launch | $0.1M | $2.1M | $3.7M |\n\nRocket Lab defines "revenue per launch" as *"the average transaction price attributable to launch contract performance obligations during the period in which the launch occurs, regardless of whether the revenue is recognized as point-in-time or over-time."* This is a directly disclosed, audited metric — not an analyst construct.\n\n---\n\n### 2. SpaceX\'s Implied Revenue-Per-Launch Proxy (Space Segment)\n\nSpaceX\'s S-1 does **not** disclose a per-launch revenue or cost metric. However, two critical facts enable construction of a proxy:\n\n- **Space segment revenue reflects only external customer launches.** Internal Starlink launches generate no inter-segment revenue; their costs are capitalized as PP&E within the Connectivity segment.\n- **Customer launch counts are disclosed separately** from internal launches.\n\nThis allows the following calculation:\n\n| Metric | FY2023 | FY2024 | FY2025 |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Total Space Segment Revenue | $3,557M | $3,796M | $4,086M |\n| Customer Launches | 33 | 45 | 43 |\n| **Implied Revenue per Customer Launch (Total Space)** | **$107.8M** | **$84.4M** | **$95.0M** |\n\nHowever, total Space segment revenue includes two sub-categories with different recognition patterns:\n\n| Sub-Category | FY2023 | FY2024 | FY2025 |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Launch Services (point-in-time) | 55.2% | 68.2% | 63.0% |\n| Launch & Development (over-time) | 44.8% | 31.8% | 37.0% |\n\nIsolating only the **Launch Services** component (recognized at point-in-time, most directly analogous to Rocket Lab\'s per-launch metric):\n\n| Metric | FY2023 | FY2024 | FY2025 |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Launch Services Revenue (est.) | $1,963M | $2,589M | $2,574M |\n| Customer Launches | 33 | 45 | 43 |\n| **Implied Launch Services Rev per Customer Launch** | **$59.5M** | **$57.5M** | **$59.9M** |\n\nThis is consistent with the S-1\'s qualitative statement that *"Space customer launches and average price per launch remained relatively flat year over year"* between 2024 and 2025.\n\n---\n\n### 3. Directional Comparison\n\n| | Rocket Lab (Electron) | SpaceX (Falcon, implied) | Ratio |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Revenue per Launch (2025)** | **$8.5M** (disclosed) | **~$59.9M** (Launch Services only) or **~$95.0M** (total Space) | **~7x to ~11x** |\n| Payload Capacity to LEO | 300 kg | ~23,000 kg (Falcon 9) / ~64,000 kg (Falcon Heavy) | ~77x to ~213x |\n| Avg. Mass per Customer Launch (2025) | Not disclosed | ~7.3 metric tons | — |\n| Vehicle Reusability | Expendable (no recovery) | 95.2% flight-proven boosters (157 of 165 Falcon launches in 2025) | — |\n| Cost per Launch (2025) | $4.8M (disclosed) | Not disclosed | — |\n\n**On a per-kilogram basis** (using SpaceX customer mass-to-orbit data):\n- SpaceX Launch Services revenue per kg to orbit (2025): ~$8,251/kg\n- SpaceX total Space revenue per kg to orbit (2025): ~$13,100/kg\n- Rocket Lab: Not calculable (mass-to-orbit per launch not disclosed), but at max 300 kg capacity and $8.5M revenue per launch, the theoretical ceiling is ~$28,333/kg — likely significantly higher in practice given typical sub-max payloads.\n\n---\n\n### 4. What the Comparison Reveals About Vertical Integration and Reusability\n\n**a) Reusability compresses cost but not necessarily price.** SpaceX\'s 95%+ flight-proven booster rate (with boosters reflown up to 34 times) dramatically reduces marginal launch cost. The S-1 emphasizes that Falcon 9 reduced cost-to-orbit to ~$2,700/kg vs. the historical industry average of ~$18,500/kg (an ~85% reduction). However, SpaceX\'s implied revenue per customer launch (~$60M for Launch Services) suggests it captures substantial value — the cost savings from reusability flow disproportionately to margin, not just to lower prices. Rocket Lab, by contrast, operates an expendable vehicle but has reduced cost per launch from $7.0M to $4.8M through manufacturing scale, achieving a ~44% gross margin in 2025.\n\n**b) Vertical integration enables capture of the full mission value chain.** SpaceX\'s Space segment revenue includes not just the launch itself but mission integration, payload handling, and potentially rideshare aggregation. The S-1 notes that SpaceX designs mission parameters around customer requirements. This vertical integration allows SpaceX to charge a premium per launch that reflects end-to-end mission value rather than just the rocket\'s marginal cost. Rocket Lab\'s Launch Services revenue similarly includes mission integration and rideshare services, but at a much smaller absolute scale.\n\n**c) The revenue-per-launch gap is primarily a function of vehicle class, not pricing power.** Falcon 9\'s ~23-ton LEO capacity vs. Electron\'s 300 kg capacity means SpaceX serves fundamentally different markets (GEO commsats, national security payloads, ISS resupply, interplanetary probes) at inherently higher price points. The ~7x revenue-per-launch differential is actually *smaller* than the ~77x payload capacity differential, suggesting SpaceX\'s reusability-driven cost structure allows it to offer more competitive per-kg pricing than an expendable vehicle of equivalent class could.\n\n**d) Internal demand absorption is unique to SpaceX.** SpaceX allocated 122 of 165 Falcon launches (74%) to internal Starlink deployment in 2025, generating zero Space segment revenue. This vertical integration of launch *demand* (not just supply) is a structural advantage no pure-play launch provider possesses. It guarantees high flight rates that amortize fixed costs and accelerate the reusability learning curve — a flywheel Rocket Lab cannot replicate.\n\n---\n\n### 5. The Missing Disclosure: What Would Make This Comparison Precise\n\nThe specific disclosure **present in Rocket Lab\'s 10-K but absent from SpaceX\'s S-1** is a **directly reported "average revenue per launch" (or "average selling price per launch") KPI**, accompanied by a **"cost per launch" KPI**.\n\nRocket Lab explicitly discloses both:\n- **Revenue per launch** (average transaction price): $8.5M (2025)\n- **Cost per launch**: $4.8M (2025)\n\nThese are defined, audited, period-over-period comparable metrics that isolate the unit economics of each launch event.\n\nSpaceX\'s S-1 would need to disclose the following to make the comparison precise rather than approximate:\n\n1. **Average revenue per customer launch** — broken out between Launch Services (point-in-time) and Launch & Development (over-time), since the latter includes multi-year government development contracts that are not per-launch transactions.\n\n2. **Customer launch count by vehicle type** (Falcon 9 vs. Falcon Heavy) — Falcon Heavy missions (e.g., NASA Europa Clipper, NSSL missions) command significantly higher prices and would skew the average upward. Without this breakdown, the implied ~$60M per launch conflates ~$50-55M Falcon 9 missions with potentially $100M+ Falcon Heavy missions.\n\n3. **Cost per customer launch** — to enable margin comparison. SpaceX\'s S-1 discloses Space segment cost of revenue in aggregate but does not normalize it to a per-launch basis.\n\n4. **Mass-to-orbit per customer launch** — to enable per-kg pricing comparison. While the S-1 discloses aggregate customer mass-to-orbit (312 metric tons in 2025), it does not disclose the distribution across missions.\n\nWithout these four disclosures, any SpaceX per-launch figure remains an **aggregate proxy** that blends vehicle types, mission profiles, contract structures (fixed-price launch services vs. over-time development contracts), and customer mix — making it directionally useful but not precisely comparable to Rocket Lab\'s cleanly isolated Electron unit economics.\n\n---\n\n### Sources\n\n{\n  "sources": [\n    {\n      "url": "https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/1181412/000162828026036936/spaceexplorationtechnologi.htm",\n      "name": "SpaceX S-1 Registration Statement (filed May 20, 2026)"\n    },\n    {\n      "url": "https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/1819994/000181999426000013/rklb-20251231.htm",\n      "name": "Rocket Lab Corp 10-K for FY2025 (filed February 26, 2026)"\n    }\n  ]\n}'})
